At the time of the procedure, no tissue was noted on the first pass, so ultrasound was performed which revealed a persistent gestational sac. A second D&C was then performed, but pathology from that procedure did not reveal villi. Pt was discharged from the PACU with reasonable pain control, but the following afternoon began having midline and right lower abdominal pain radiating to her low back. The pain was strong enough to bring her to tears. She had two episodes of emesis associated with the pain. Pain did not respond to perocoet. Denies fevers, chills, vaginal bleeding, unusual vaginal discharge. Upon arrival to the ___, her VS were stable at T 96.8 HR 91 BP 135/83 RR 17 POx 100%. She received 2mg of dilaudid with improvement in the pain. She denied nausea and vomiting, but had radiation of the pain to her low back. 
 **Past Medical History**: ObHx: LTCS (IUI pregnancy) GynHx: PCOS. Distant hx of abnormal Pap, normal since. No history of STIs. MedHx: PE/DVT after gastric bypass, PCOS, migraines, IBS, diverticulutis SurgHx: D&C as above, gastric bypass, multiple cystoscopies, laproscopic cholecystectomy, exploratory laparotomy x 2 (one with appendectomy), diagnostic laparoscopy, ventral hernia repair with mesh
